05432nam a22008055i 9780824860790DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248607907 a10.1515/97808248607902doi  a(DE-B1597)484563  a(OCoLC)1024052009  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL782.E1bI58 2011 7aLCO0040002bisacsh04a895.6/080895722200aInto the Light :bAn Anthology of Literature by Koreans in Japan /ced. by Melissa L. Wender. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Translations -- tIntroduction -- tInto the Light (1939) -- tIn the Shadow of Mount Fuji (1951) -- tForeign Husband (1958) -- tFrozen Mouth (1966) -- tThe Korean Women I Love (1974) -- tTestament (1984) -- tName: For Pak Ch’u-ja (1984) -- tKoku (1984) -- tFull House (1997) -- tAdditional Readings on Zainichi Korean Literature -- tAbout the Translators0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInto the Light is the first anthology to introduce the fiction of Japan’s Korean community (Zainichi Koreans) to the English-speaking world. The collection brings together works by many of the most important Zainichi Korean writers of the twentieth century, from the colonial-era "Into the Light" (1939) by Kim Sa-ryang to "Full House" (1997) by Yu Miri, one of contemporary Japan’s most acclaimed and popular authors.Although diverse in style and subject matter, all of the stories gathered in this volume ask a single consuming question: What does it mean to be Korean in Japan? Some stories record their contemporary milieu, while others focus on internal turmoil or document social and legal discrimination. More generally, they consider the relationship of Korean ethnicity to sexuality, family, culture, politics, and history. Thus the stories provide a fascinating window into the human experience of modernity in Japan and Korea, not only enabling us to track the ways in which grand concepts such as nation, language, empire, economy, and gender have shaped the human imagination, but also entreating us to ask how individual authors have sought to provide insight—or even guidance—on the path that grand history might follow.The volume includes stories by Chong Ch’u-wol, Kim Ch’ang-saeng, Kim Hak-yong, Kim Sa-ryang, Kim Tal-su, Noguchi Kakuchu, Yi Yang-ji, and Yu Miri.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJapanese literaturexKorean authorsvTranslations into English. 0aJapanese literaturey20th centuryvTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aCh’u-wŏl, Chong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHak-yŏng, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKakuchū, Noguchi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiri, Yū, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSa-ryang, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTal-su, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWender, Melissa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWender, Melissa L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYang-ji, Yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uh